Based on the position, one pressing issue is that White’s bishop on f1 is already aiming along the f1–a6 diagonal and could capture the pawn on c4 on the next move. To prevent that, a good idea is to reinforce the pawn by using the pawn on b7. By advancing it two squares to b5, not only do we develop on the queenside, but the pawn on b5 will then defend c4 (since from b5 it defends a4 and c4 along the diagonal) and solidify our structure.

Thus, I’ll play:

- 'get_legal_moves' to get a UCI formatted list of available moves
- 'make_move <UCI formatted move>' when you are ready to complete your turn (e.g., 'make_move e2e4')

• The knight on g5 can legally jump to e6 (with the destination square e6 empty).
• From e6, the knight’s attack pattern includes f4, so the white king on f4 is in check.
• Forcing a check can limit white’s options and give Black an opportunity to dictate the game’s pace.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll start by checking one promising idea. Notice that the queen on g1 is currently blocked from reaching the diagonal that “hits” the white king on b7 by our own pawn on c5. However, if we don’t want to wait a move to clear that diagonal, we can try a different queen route.

One very effective move is to reposition our queen from g1 to h1. (In UCI notation that’s “g1h1”.) Why is that good? Look at it this way:

• In standard algebraic coordinates (with the top row as rank 8 and the bottom row as rank 1), the white king sits on b7. On the diagonal a8–b7–c6–d5–e4–f3–g2–h1 the sum of file+rank is always 9. (For example, b7 is (2,7) so 2+7=9.)  
• Moving our queen from g1 (which is (7,1) with sum 8) to h1 (which is (8,1) so 8+1=9) puts her square on that same diagonal.  
• Once on h1 the queen “looks” along that entire diagonal, and since b7 lies on it the white king is now in check. Moreover, the path h1→g2→f3→e4→d5→c6→b7 is clear (none of those squares are obstructed by any piece).

After Qh1+ the white king’s possible moves (from its eight adjacent squares) are reduced because the queen’s diagonal controls a8 and c6, among others. (Even though white will have some moves left, our overwhelming material advantage will easily decide the game in the following moves.)

So as Black, a strong move is:

  make_move g1h1

This queen move to h1 delivers a diagonal check to the white king on b7 and improves our mating prospects.

- 'get_legal_moves' to get a UCI formatted list of available moves
- 'make_move <UCI formatted move>' when you are ready to complete your turn (e.g., 'make_move e2e4')

get_current_board

make_move d5d7

This moves my queen from d5 to d7. Notice that from d7 the queen lines up along the 7th rank to check the white king on a7, and because d7 is adjacent to my king on e7, the white king is prevented from capturing the queen.

I'll choose to improve our position by repositioning the bishop so that it can later support a checking rook move. Moving the bishop from b8 to c7 has the benefit that once it sits on c7 it defends the a5‐square. This means that when I later swing the rook from a6 to a5 with check, if the white king tries to capture the rook on a5 it will be recaptured by my bishop on c7. 

Therefore, I’ll play:

make_move b8c7

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, I see that our queen sits on f3 and our king on f7 with pawns on a4, c4, h7, and h5. White’s only piece is the king on h2. In queen‑and‑king versus lone king endgames, a standard plan is to use the queen to cut off the enemy king’s escape routes and drive it toward a mating net—usually forcing it into a corner—while then bringing our king closer for support.

A move I’m considering is to use our queen to deliver an immediate check that restricts the white king’s options. One candidate is to play Qf3–f2 (in UCI notation: “f3f2”). After Qf2+, white’s king (currently at h2) has very few safe squares. In fact, its only moves appear to be to h1 or h3, and both these moves let us continue our plan of drying up its escape squares and eventually forcing mate soon.

Thus, I’ll play:

make_move f3f2

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board position, I notice that our queen on c4 is currently in the line of the white bishop on f1. The bishop’s northwest diagonal goes f1–e2–d3–c4, so if we leave the queen there the bishop will capture it on the next move. We must step our queen away from that dangerous diagonal.

One natural idea is to reposition our queen to a safe, central square. For example, moving the queen from c4 to d4 (i.e. “c4d4”) moves her off that diagonal while remaining active in the center. (Other moves like Qb4 or Qc5 might be possible as well, but Qd4 seems to be both safe and active.) 

Therefore, I will make the move:

make_move c4d4

This move uses your pawn on d5 to capture White’s pawn on e4. By doing so you not only eliminate a center pawn but also avoid trading your bishop for a pawn should you try Bxe4 (since after Bxe4, White’s pawn on d3 could recapture, giving you an unfavorable exchange). 

I now complete Black’s turn with:

- 'get_legal_moves' to get a UCI formatted list of available moves
- 'make_move <UCI formatted move>' when you are ready to complete your turn (e.g., 'make_move e2e4')

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, one promising idea is to give a check with the queen in such a way that if White wanted to capture it the move would be illegal (because the queen lands on a square defended by our king). In our position the Black king on e3 defends all adjacent squares, so moving the queen to f2 (with Qf2, going from f3 to f2) is a very attractive check.

Let’s look quickly at the idea:

• The queen on f3 can go straight down to f2. (f3→f2 is legal and its path is clear.)  
• On f2 the queen checks the White king (located on h2) because they share rank 2.  
• Now, if White tries to capture the queen by moving KxQ on f2, that would place White’s king adjacent to our king (since the Black king on e3 controls f2). Thus capturing our queen would be illegal.  
• White’s only replies are to move the king elsewhere. A brief look shows that after Qf2, White’s king’s safe moves are limited to h1 or h3.

This move forces White into an awkward retreat and keeps our overwhelming material advantage.

Therefore, my selected move is: 

make_move f3f2

By playing the move “c5b5” (moving the rook horizontally from c5 to b5), you put White’s king on b2 in check along the b‐file. White must then decide between moving the king or interposing a piece. For instance, if White uses the rook on d4 to block along b4, you can capture it with …Rxb4 and win the exchange. The path – from e4 through f3 and g2 to h1 – is unobstructed. By playing  e4h1, Black would win the exchange (a rook for a bishop). Even if White recaptures with the king (from g1 to h1), the material gain and the resulting positional issues for White’s king make this move attractive.

I’ll now execute that plan.

make_move e4h1

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll begin by noting a tactical concern: the black bishop sitting on f2 is very exposed, as it’s only one square away from the white king on e2. (Remember that in Unicode, the white king is ♔ and the black bishop is ♝; f2 is adjacent to e2.) If I leave it there, white can capture it on the following move. To avoid losing material for free I want to relocate that bishop to a safe yet active square.

A good candidate is moving the bishop from f2 to g3. On g3 the bishop is no longer immediately capturable by the king (g3 isn’t adjacent to e2) while still remaining active on the long diagonal. This also keeps options open for future counter‑play – for example, it may later help support a queen check along the diagonal if circumstances allow.

Thus, I choose to move the bishop from f2 to g3.

make_move f2g3

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Proxy (to Player_Black):

Move made, switching player

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the position, Black is massively ahead (with a king, rook, bishop, and six pawns versus White’s lone king) and simply needs to keep improving the coordination to force a mate. Although there isn’t a mate‐in‐one here, one typical idea in such winning endgames is to bring your king closer in order to help the rook “box in” the enemy king. In our current position the Black king sits on g8 and its only available moves (its one‐square neighbors) are f8 and h8 (since f7, g7, and h7 are all occupied by pawns). Moving to f8 is preferable because it centralizes your king slightly more and will help support a future rook “cut‐off” along the e–file (after you eventually free the e–file by repositioning your bishop or otherwise).

Thus, as Black my move is to improve my king’s position by playing:

  make_move g8f8

This move does not give an immediate check but is a very sound step in converting the overwhelming advantage by gradually restricting the White king’s movement and preparing a decisive mating net.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current position, one idea is to clear the e‐file so that your rook on e8 can join the attack along the first rank while still keeping the white king’s escape squares (f2 and g1) blocked by your bishop. Right now your bishop on e3 covers f2 and g1, but it’s blocking the vertical line on the e‑file. Moving your bishop out of e3 onto d2 does two things at once: 

• It vacates e3 so that later you can swing your rook down (for example, with …Rxe1+), and 
• It defends the e1 square (since a bishop on d2 attacks e1), making it harder for the white king to capture your rook if it gives check there.

As a professional Black, a strong move in this position is to play:

  make_move e3d2

This move prepares your mate–net ideas by unblocking your rook’s way while keeping key squares covered.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board position, I’ve taken a look at Black’s options. (Using standard board coordinates with rank 8 at the top and rank 1 at the bottom, we have Black’s king on e6 and Black’s pawns on a5 and d4.) 

A brief summary of key points:
• The Black king on e6 is presently the only piece that can really maneuver—your pawn on d4 is blocked by an enemy pawn and pawn a5’s only move is to push forward (a5–a4), a quiet advance.
• When considering the king’s moves from e6, note that a king can move one square in any direction but cannot move into a square attacked by an enemy piece or adjacent to the enemy king.
• Checking the adjacent squares from e6 (which would normally be: d7, e7, f7, d6, f6, d5, e5, f5), several possibilities turn out to be unsafe:
  – e6–d5, e6–e5, and e6–f5 would bring your king adjacent to White’s king on e4.
  – d7 is covered by White’s pawn on c6 (since White’s pawn from c6 can capture diagonally to d7),
  – d6 and f6 fall under the control of White’s pawn on e5 (which attacks diagonally—i.e., its capture squares from e5 are d6 and f6).
• This leaves e6–e7 and e6–f7 as the only king moves that do not step into an attack.
• Meanwhile, the advance a5–a4 is legal but rather passive and does nothing to improve King safety. In an endgame with very few pieces, king activity is crucial.

I lean toward centralizing and improving the king’s position. Moving the king from e6 to e7 (i.e. "e6e7") seems to be the best choice because it keeps the king active, safely away from enemy control, and not running into the pawn attack zones.

I’ll now play:

make_move e6e7

Based on the current board layout (with rank 8 as the top row and rank 1 as the bottom row), black’s pieces are:

• King on f7  
• Pawn on a5  
• Pawn on d4  

The legal moves are:

• King moves from f7 to one of: e7, g7, or g6 (moving to any square on the 8th rank is prohibited because white’s rook on c8 controls the entire rank)  
• Pawn move a5→a4 (the pawn on d4 is blocked and has no diagonal captures)

As a professional black player in this position, I’d choose to improve king safety by shifting the king toward a secure square on the kingside. After analyzing the options, moving the king from f7 to g7 (UCI: f7g7) appears safe and avoids the direct influence of white’s rook on the 8th rank.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, your black pieces consist of a king on f2 and pawns on a4 and d4. (Remember that white’s pieces are the rooks on e8 and g6, bishop on b5, king on d5, and pawns on e5, a3, d3.) Neither of your pawns can advance (the pawn on a4 is blocked on a3, and the pawn on d4 is blocked on d3 and has no enemy piece to capture diagonally), so your only available moves are with your king from f2.

From f2 the king’s adjacent squares are:
 • e1  • f1  • g1
 • e2     g2
 • e3  • f3  • g3

A quick look at the white pieces’ control shows:
 – The bishop on b5 controls e2 and f1 (as well as a4 and parts of the opposite diagonal). 
 – The rook on g6, placed on the g‐file, attacks along g6–g5–g4–g3–g2–g1.
Thus, among the king’s moves:
 • f1, g1, e2, g2, and g3 are off‐limits.
This leaves e1, e3, and f3 as legal king moves.

Choosing among these moves from a strategic standpoint might involve considerations like king safety and potential checks. Moving toward the edge sometimes reduces the number of squares from which an opponent’s piece can check—so a move like f2 to e1 can be a reasonable attempt to tuck your king in a relatively “safer” corner.

Accordingly, one good move for Black is to play the king from f2 to e1.

Thus, the UCI move is: make_move f2e1

- 'get_legal_moves' to get a UCI formatted list of available moves
- 'make_move <UCI formatted move>' when you are ready to complete your turn (e.g., 'make_move e2e4')

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board, one promising idea is to use our knight to help further restrict the white king’s escape routes. Notice that our knight on f5 has several options, but many of them either leave white’s king too many safe squares or send our knight toward a less useful central position. Moving the knight to h6 (i.e. from f5 to h6) is attractive because once on h6 it immediately covers the squares f5, f7, g4, and even g8—so from white’s king at g5 many adjacent squares will be denied (for example, g4 and f5 become “poisoned”). In fact, after 1…Nf5–h6 the only “safe” moves for the white king will be to h4 or h5.

Thus, I will play:

make_move f5h6

This move restricts the white king’s mobility and improves our mating net prospects.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Proxy (to Player_Black):

Move made, switching player

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board position, one idea is to improve the king’s safety. Notice that the white rook on d8 controls the entire 8th rank, so keeping the black king off that rank is important. By moving the king from f7 to g6, Black not only steps away from the rook’s potential checks but also avoids exchanges (such as the pawn capture on b4 that would allow White’s bishop on a3 to recapture) which would further simplify into a winning endgame for White.

Thus, a good move in this position is:

make_move f7g6

- 'get_legal_moves' to get a UCI formatted list of available moves
- 'make_move <UCI formatted move>' when you are ready to complete your turn (e.g., 'make_move e2e4')

• The knight on g3 has a legal move to h1 (moving +1 file and −2 ranks), capturing the white rook that sits on h1.
• A white rook is a valuable piece, and it doesn’t appear to be defended immediately by any white piece.
• After playing g3h1, if needed the knight can always escape via f2 (or even back to g3) on its next move.

This capture nets us a significant material advantage. 

Let’s proceed with that plan.

make_move g3h1

 Rank8: ⭘ ⭘ ♔ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘     (a8, b8, c8, …, h8)
 Rank7: ♟ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ♚ ⭘     (a7, ..., g7, …)

Here the white king sits on c8, your pawn is on a7, and your king is on g7. In many king-and-pawn endings, coordinating your king with the pawn is essential for a win. I therefore choose to improve the king’s position by moving it toward the center and eventually the queenside, where it can aid the pawn’s advance.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll choose to play Qd7#. That is, I'll move my queen from a7 to d7.

To explain briefly:
• The white king is on d8, and its available adjacent squares normally would be c8, d7, e8, c7, and e7.
• My black king on c6 controls c7 and d7.
• By playing my queen to d7 along the 7th rank (a legal horizontal move), my queen then covers:
  – Horizontally, the entire 7th rank (so c7, d7, e7 are attacked),
  – Vertically along file d (so d8 is attacked), and
  – Diagonally it covers both c8 and e8.
Thus every square the white king might escape to is covered, and white cannot capture my queen (since d7 is protected by my king on c6).

This move is checkmate.

make_move a7d7
